Structure Classification — Frozen Specification (Final)
1. Purpose
Determines which confirmed swings remain structurally relevant (unbroken) and maintains their lifecycle, independent of and downstream from swing confirmation itself.
2. Lifecycle
Two states: Active → Retired, terminal. No reactivation.
3. Activation Rule
Every swing reaching STATUS_CONFIRMED in the Swing Database becomes Active, unconditionally, on the same bar that confirmation is observed.
4. Retirement Rule
A swing retires when, and only when, price closes beyond its level in the invalidating direction (above the level for a confirmed high, below for a confirmed low). Wick-only interaction never retires a swing. Exact equality (close == level) is not a retirement event — strict inequality required, consistent with the same tie-break rule already frozen in BOS.
5. Multiplicity
Multiple concurrently active swings per side (high and low independently) are supported without restriction — this is a domain requirement, not an implementation convenience.
6. Break Computation
A shared, pure, stateless utility (deriveLevelCrossed) computes the crossing fact. Structure Classification is its first consumer. BOS's existing frozen implementation is left untouched — this utility is available for future consumers (Liquidity, CHoCH) but does not retroactively modify BOS.
7. Ownership — swingStructureLabel
Not owned by Structure Classification. Remains reserved for a separate, not-yet-scheduled extension to the Swing Database's finalizeConfirmedSwing().
8. Direction
Not persisted anywhere. Derived at read time from swingType (SWING_HIGH → "bullish", SWING_LOW → "bearish"), solely to preserve BOS's existing frozen string-based contract.
9. Active-Set Cap (Question 6 — resolved for this implementation)
No cap implemented. Draft v5 established no domain-derived cap exists; inventing an arbitrary number now would be an unjustified engineering assumption. The active set is allowed to grow unbounded in this version. This is a disclosed, intentional deferral — not an oversight — and should be revisited if real data shows problematic growth.
10. Execution Order Within a Bar (Question 9 — resolved for this implementation)
Activation runs first, then retirement scans the full set including anything just activated, using the same bar's close. This ensures a swing that confirms already-invalidated by that bar's price action retires immediately rather than lingering one extra bar as falsely "active."
11. Complexity — Honest Disclosure
The retirement scan is O(n) in total historical swing count, not O(k)-active-only, because entries are never removed from the underlying array (retired swings remain as permanent historical records, per the immutability principle). This mirrors an already-accepted, already-documented performance characteristic elsewhere in this project (the Swing Database's own swingIndexFromId is similarly O(n)) — not a new risk class, but worth tracking under the same future optimization umbrella if it matters at scale.
12. Integration Point — Named Explicitly
Activation detection consumes the Replacement Engine's existing per-bar currentConfirmedSwingIds/currentConfirmedSwingBars arrays (already built for visualization, cleared each bar via resetCurrentBarEvents()) — the actual, concrete mechanism by which this module learns "which swings confirmed this bar," rather than an abstract placeholder.
13. Confirmed-Bar Field Resolution
This module's own activatedBar is the bar on which this module observed confirmation — the true confirmation-bar index — distinct from the Swing Database's swingBar (the pivot's own bar). This resolves a gap flagged in the project's original architecture review (no field previously captured true confirmation-bar timing).
14. Ordering Guarantee to BOS
structcls_getActiveStructuralSwingIds() returns IDs in ascending swing_id / insertion order — deterministic, satisfying the cross-module ordering obligation recorded at Sprint 2.5's closeout.
15. Known Follow-Up (not part of this implementation)
bos_isLifecycleConfirmed()'s comparison (lifecycle_state == "Confirmed") will need a one-line update to compare against the Swing Database's actual STATUS_CONFIRMED int constant once real integration occurs — this is the exact representation-swap seam that adapter was designed to absorb, per its own frozen documentation. Not performed here, since it means editing already-frozen BOS code, out of scope for this deliverable.

